				<p class="questioner">Reply by <a href="user_page.html" rel="next">Joss Whedon </a>on Nov. 23, 2013</p>
			
<p>At least in California -- you can access it. In the past, I've requested video surveillance footage of a crime that occurred in downtown San Diego. It was captured by the local transportation agency's camera outside a trolley station. I also just requested surveillance footage from the same agency of footage from buses and trolleys. They appear to be honoring that request, as well.</p>

<blockquote>The problem is, a lot of times these government agencies use third-party software. So when you request the footage, the files may come in a format you've never seen or heard of and you'll have to scrounge around for a way to play them.</blockquote>

<p>To request, simply file a Public Records Act request for the footage. But keep in mind they do re-use a lot of the tapes if there is no reason to keep them, so only footage of crimes would be kept. Daily activity would not last for more than a couple weeks, most likely, before being erased and used again.<p>

<p>Hope that helps.</p>

